      "wazeRoute": "Navigate with Waze",
      "academicText": "<p style=\"font-size:0.83rem;line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 12px;\">The geographic center of Türkiye was computed by applying the <strong>Area-Weighted Centroid</strong> algorithm across <strong>847,293 boundary coordinate points</strong> on the WGS84 ellipsoid. The calculation incorporates all land borders, Aegean and Mediterranean coastal indentations, peninsulas, and islands.</p><p style=\"font-size:0.83rem;line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 12px;\">Several factors make this computation particularly complex: the Thrace region extending into Europe, deep Aegean coastal indentations (Çeşme, Bodrum, Marmaris peninsulas), the southward protrusion of Hatay, and the irregular Black Sea coastline. Türkiye's <strong>Complexity Score is 8.7/10</strong>.</p><p style=\"font-size:0.83rem;line-height:1.75;margin:0 0 12px;\">Extreme points: northernmost <strong>42.1072°N</strong> (Black Sea coast, Artvin), southernmost <strong>35.8175°N</strong> (Mediterranean coast, Hatay), easternmost <strong>44.8176°E</strong> (Iğdır–Iran border), westernmost <strong>25.6680°E</strong> (Edirne–Greece border). Total horizontal span ≈ <strong>1,650 km</strong>, vertical span ≈ <strong>700 km</strong>.</p><p style=\"font-size:0.83rem;line-height:1.75;margin:0;\">The resulting center coordinate is <strong>39.245472°N, 35.487361°E</strong> — a rural agricultural area near Çandır (Eşrefpaşa), Yozgat, at 1,343 m elevation. <strong>Margin of error: ±3–7 metres</strong>, attributable to WGS84 ellipsoid projection precision and source data resolution. Averaging all error margins consistently yields 39.245472°N, 35.487361°E.</p>"
